                    <p>
                        DNA is composed of two directional strands. The directionality of these strands is dictated by the orientation of the <a href="#nucleotide">nucleotides</a> that compose it; there is a <a href="#5_prime_end_5">5' end</a> and a <a href="#5_prime_end_5">3' end</a>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Four different <a href="#nucleotide">nucleotides</a> compose DNA, these are differentiated by the nucleic bases they hold: <a href="#adenine">adenine (A)</a>, <a href="#thymine">thymine (T)</a>, <a href="#guanine">guanine (G)</a>, and <a href="#cytosine">cytosine (C)</a>. These can grouped together chemically into the purine group A, T, and the pyrimidine group G, C. The two strands come together and bind through weak <a href="#hydrogenBond">hydrogen bonds</a>; A - T (2 bonds), and C - G (3 bonds).
                    </p>